WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.437 --> 00:00:07.760
[Music]

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:14.400
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. As you probably&nbsp;
suspect, I'm not a big fan of 20th-century&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:19.520
mathematical work at the foundational&nbsp;
level. I think that we are collectively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:26.640
living in a dream world with objects and&nbsp;
constructions that aren't pegged down to reality.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:32.640
One of the jobs of this foundational&nbsp;
series is to try to move us gently—or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:39.280
perhaps not so gently—in a more&nbsp;
realistic and more honest direction. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:46.640
one of the aspects of this that I'm going to talk&nbsp;
about today is the movement from a 20th-century&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:53.920
object-oriented point of view to a 21st-century&nbsp;
expression-oriented point of view. I want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.920 --> 00:01:01.120
tell you what those terms mean to me and give&nbsp;
you some applications of these thinkings to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:07.920
algebraic curves. We're ultimately wanting&nbsp;
to understand algebraic curves in a good way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:13.440
and this is a very pertinent discussion even&nbsp;
though it's sort of at the metamathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:19.200
level. I won't actually be giving mathematically&nbsp;
precise definitions of these terms—object-oriented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:23.600
and expression-oriented—but I hope you'll get&nbsp;
the gist of it, and it will resonate with you.

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:30.800
Okay, so very roughly, one of the&nbsp;
aspects of 20th-century mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:36.320
is that it has been object-oriented. People&nbsp;
have had this idea that there are mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:42.640
objects that are "out there." They're often almost&nbsp;
physical in the sense that we can picture them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:48.320
maybe we can graph them or we can model them,&nbsp;
and the idea is that we should try to model&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:54.320
those inside mathematics. So, we take the abstract&nbsp;
picture, and we try to build up some structures&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:59.440
that reflect as accurately as&nbsp;
possible these images that we have.

00:02:01.520 --> 00:02:06.080
I believe that 21st-century mathematics is going&nbsp;
to take a quite different approach to things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:11.200
where the primary things of interest&nbsp;
are not necessarily mathematical objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:13.360
but rather mathematical expressions.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.480
Now, 20th-century mathematics, of course, has many&nbsp;
good things about it and many things also not so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:27.600
good about it. Some of the things that are not&nbsp;
so good about it are that it's based on Cantor's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:34.560
set theory and sort of a notion of functions&nbsp;
that goes along with set theory. This is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:40.000
unfortunately, an infinite set theory,&nbsp;
and it has all kinds of waffly aspects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:43.680
all kinds of imprecisions associated&nbsp;
with it. There are all kinds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:51.120
wrong habits of thinking associated with this.&nbsp;
Unfortunately, it's become very much an orthodoxy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:55.040
and I'm going to have an uphill&nbsp;
battle trying to convince you to think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:59.760
clearly about this subject from the beginning&nbsp;
again. Nevertheless, I will try to do that.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:07.040
Another aspect of 20th-century mathematics is that&nbsp;
it has a very descriptive approach to definitions.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:16.080
Definitions in the 20th century are sometimes&nbsp;
not much away from being descriptions;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.040 --> 00:03:21.040
there is not really a distinction between&nbsp;
a description and a specification.

00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:27.440
In the 21st century, I believe that&nbsp;
specifications and definitions will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:32.640
be much closer together. People will not&nbsp;
be looking for a sort of a painting of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:37.440
definition but actually asking the question,&nbsp;
"How do we specify mathematical objects?"

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:47.280
20th-century mathematics has the idea that&nbsp;
we try to lock in interpretations. We have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:52.720
some mathematical object, and we want to lock in&nbsp;
an interpretation of that mathematical object.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:59.280
I believe 21st-century mathematics is going&nbsp;
to be more flexible and going to allow—and in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:05.120
fact encourage—multiple interpretations&nbsp;
of the expressions that are involved.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:12.880
You'll see what I mean; I'm going to amplify&nbsp;
this to some extent, but I just want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:16.000
lay this out for now to give&nbsp;
you something to think about.

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:21.440
20th-century mathematics has also been very&nbsp;
oriented towards human visual and tactile&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:30.000
processing. The models and the arguments that are&nbsp;
used are often very close to visual reasoning.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:34.960
I believe that in the 21st century,&nbsp;
we're going to have to move to a more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:41.840
computer-oriented frame of mind, where it's&nbsp;
less human-centered and more computer-centered.

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:47.920
In fact, sort of when in doubt about a&nbsp;
mathematical construct or a mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:54.240
definition or mathematical argument, when there's&nbsp;
debate about whether something makes sense or not,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.520 --> 00:05:02.480
I think a good way of going forward on that is to&nbsp;
ask ourselves, "Can we encode this on a computer?"&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:08.960
Is your definition precise enough, clear&nbsp;
enough, that somebody can encode it on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:14.400
a computer? Is your computation explicit&nbsp;
enough that it can be encoded on a computer?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:22.320
It's some kind of litmus test that gives us&nbsp;
more certainty than a lot of talk. There's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:30.640
lot of talk in 20th-century mathematics, which&nbsp;
is largely unsupported by computer equivalence.

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:38.160
Alright, so I want to explain some of this&nbsp;
business. It's going to take me more than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:43.840
one video to do that—there are many aspects of&nbsp;
this—but it's a general orientation that I've had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:48.640
throughout this series. You've probably&nbsp;
noticed it in several spots. Now it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.640 --> 00:05:53.680
time to be a little bit more specific about what&nbsp;
the differences are and how it manifests itself.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.120 --> 00:06:00.720
Today, we're going to look at this distinction in&nbsp;
rather only one special direction—the direction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:06.240
that we've been talking about in the last few&nbsp;
videos having to do with algebraic curves. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:11.520
sort of the application that we have in mind, but&nbsp;
in fact, I'll have a lot more to say about this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:17.760
in subsequent videos on other aspects of&nbsp;
mathematics. But for today, we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:24.160
to look at how does this actually sort of&nbsp;
practically look like in our study of curves,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:30.240
and to make things very simple, we're going&nbsp;
to keep things down to the simplest curves.

00:06:31.360 --> 00:06:38.560
So, let's have a good look at a very simple&nbsp;
example—the unit circle. What is the unit circle?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:48.560
In the 20th century, of course, we have this&nbsp;
pictorial representation of it, what we draw in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:56.160
the xy Cartesian plane, but the actual definition&nbsp;
of it in most textbooks will be pretty well this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.160 --> 00:07:03.920
one here. To the 20th-century mathematician,&nbsp;
a circle is a set. It's a set of points.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:15.280
So, it's the set of points (x, y) where x and&nbsp;
y are real numbers that satisfy x² + y² = 1.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.840
Alright, there are all kinds of problems with&nbsp;
real numbers that eventually we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:30.880
talk at length about, but let's accept&nbsp;
that for now. So, what does this mean?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:38.480
Well, it's a set, so it's got a lot of elements,&nbsp;
and each element in the set looks like this. It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:45.840
a point, so it's got some brackets, and inside&nbsp;
the brackets are two numbers, and those are real&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:52.000
numbers, and they have to have this property.&nbsp;
Alright, so inside this set, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:59.040
we would find the point (1, 0) because 1&nbsp;
and 0 satisfy this equation. We'd also find&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:13.600
(0, 1), we'd find (3/5, 4/5), we'd find (1/√2,&nbsp;
1/√2), we'd find (5/13, -12/13), (0, -1), but of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:20.320
course, this is sort of unrepresentative. Most of&nbsp;
the numbers here are wildly much more complicated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:26.080
than these ones. So, for example, you can let x&nbsp;
be pretty well anything as long as it's in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.080 --> 00:08:35.600
range between -1 and 1, say e^-2, and then y will&nbsp;
have to be something like √(1 - e^-4). So, you can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:40.480
write down something like that, and then you think&nbsp;
of this set as sort of carrying on and on and on.

00:08:43.920 --> 00:08:49.360
That's what a circle is. So, if you want to write&nbsp;
down what the circle is, you really are obliged&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:55.200
to write down this set. Of course, we can never&nbsp;
write down this set because of the complexity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.200 --> 00:09:01.360
involved in these three little dots which are&nbsp;
just tucked away back here almost beyond notice.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:08.720
But it's these three little dots, of course, that&nbsp;
contain all the complexity—that vast collection&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.720 --> 00:09:13.440
of bigger and bigger ordered pairs&nbsp;
with wilder and wilder numbers in them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:19.440
In fact, this is not really an honest&nbsp;
representation at all because it suggests&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:29.200
that you can actually list the pairs in some kind&nbsp;
of order. Well, according to the standard dogma,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:35.680
this infinite set that we're talking about is not&nbsp;
really at all of this kind. This is not actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:43.040
countable, according to the standard dogma.&nbsp;
Okay, so what that means is that the level of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:50.720
infinity that's supposedly being involved here is&nbsp;
larger than the infinity of natural numbers. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:53.600 --> 00:09:57.120
so even this representation is&nbsp;
somehow completely inadequate.

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:09.520
This kind of idea is very much a&nbsp;
20th-century idea. In previous centuries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:15.520
older civilizations would never have thought&nbsp;
about it this way. I'm not sure how they would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:15.520 --> 00:10:23.040
have explained what a circle is, but certainly&nbsp;
not in this way. This is vastly too complicated,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:31.840
and there's somehow dishonesty oozing&nbsp;
out of all corners of this definition.

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:36.160
But repetition renders the ridiculous reasonable.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:42.960
If you repeat something, even if it doesn't make&nbsp;
a lot of sense, but you repeat it enough times,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:47.520
eventually it starts sounding&nbsp;
more and more reasonable.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:54.480
The young student today, the mathematics&nbsp;
student, is exposed to this kind of set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.480 --> 00:10:58.400
repeatedly, over and over. Everything&nbsp;
is defined in terms of some kind of set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:08.640
so you become oblivious eventually to the logical&nbsp;
obscurity of the concept. A circle, to an artist,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:13.600
is something that's continuous. It's something&nbsp;
that you draw like this. It's not something that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:20.480
you create by drawing a lot of points. This is&nbsp;
like a pointless kind of definition, where you're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:27.280
making a lot of points like this—like the&nbsp;
Impressionist school of painting, which was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:34.240
quite popular for a little while. This is really a&nbsp;
pointless definition and somehow does not reflect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:36.560 --> 00:11:43.760
the physical aspect of what we're doing when we're&nbsp;
drawing a circle. There's something very fishy and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:53.360
very unpleasant, really, about such a definition.&nbsp;
In my opinion, it's way too complicated.

00:11:54.240 --> 00:12:00.400
So, I believe that in the 21st century, we're&nbsp;
going to move back to a simpler and more naive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:06.720
approach to things like the unit circle.&nbsp;
Earlier generations would have said, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:13.200
a unit circle—the essential part of it is this&nbsp;
equation here. It's this equation here that really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:13.200 --> 00:12:21.200
captures the circle, and some mathematicians&nbsp;
would have said that the circle is that equation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:27.360
And I think that's a definition that needs to&nbsp;
be taken seriously—that the circle really is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:27.360 --> 00:12:36.000
encapsulated by this equation. And that equation&nbsp;
is really reflecting the circle. This is a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:41.600
simpler than some vast infinite set with all&nbsp;
kinds of complicated ordered pairs in it.

00:12:43.200 --> 00:12:48.080
However, we want to go a little bit further&nbsp;
because this thing here already has some ambiguity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:53.680
in it because of the x and the y, which are&nbsp;
variables—not something that we've really pinned&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.680 --> 00:13:00.560
down. But we know that we can replace something&nbsp;
like this with an associated poly number—actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:07.040
a bipoly number, but I won't always say that. So,&nbsp;
instead of x, we might use alpha; instead of y,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:07.040 --> 00:13:13.120
we might use beta. And then we're really&nbsp;
talking about this bipoly number: (-1, 0, 1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:25.760
(0, 1). So, this little bipoly number&nbsp;
really kind of encodes the circle.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:33.680
However, there's a bit of ambiguity left because&nbsp;
we can, in fact, scale this equation and still&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:38.960
have the same circle. In other words, if you come&nbsp;
along and you multiply both sides of this equation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:47.360
by 2, for example, you get 2x² + 2y² = 2. That&nbsp;
also defines exactly the same circle, and this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:47.360 --> 00:13:55.520
equation corresponds to the poly number 2P = (-2,&nbsp;
0, 2), (0, 2). If we bring everything to one side.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:57.120 --> 00:14:01.520
So, if we're going to associate the circle&nbsp;
with a poly number, should we associate it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:06.240
with this one, or should we associate it&nbsp;
with this one, or some other multiple?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:07.360 --> 00:14:12.240
Because the actual poly number that we&nbsp;
use, if we scale it, we get the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:17.280
geometrical object. So, we have to&nbsp;
incorporate that somehow into the definition.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:24.320
So, we're going to make a small modification to&nbsp;
the idea of a poly number or a bipoly number.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:27.040
We're going to talk about&nbsp;
a projective bipoly number.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:34.160
So, here's a projective bipoly number. It&nbsp;
looks a lot like a bipoly number except that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:34.160 --> 00:14:39.520
instead of having one half bracket around&nbsp;
it, it has a double half bracket around it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:46.400
That's going to be our convention. That&nbsp;
tells us that this thing is unchanged&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:51.840
if we multiply it by a non-zero number. So,&nbsp;
we're going to agree that this double bracket&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:59.680
tells us that we are allowed to multiply the thing&nbsp;
by any non-zero number, and it doesn't change.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:06.480
So, this projective bipoly number is the same&nbsp;
as this projective bipoly number, which is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:06.480 --> 00:15:14.560
same as this one, and we might just use a capital&nbsp;
P instead of a small p for the projective object.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:23.680
Okay, so now we can say, what is a unit circle?&nbsp;
Here's a 21st-century definition, which is not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.680 --> 00:15:28.000
really that much different from a probably&nbsp;
17th-century definition or an 18th-century&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:32.560
definition, except it's a little bit more&nbsp;
formalized, a little bit more computer-amenable.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:39.600
The unit circle is the projective bipoly number&nbsp;
C, this one right here: (-1, 0, 1), (0, 1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:46.160
with the double brackets telling us&nbsp;
it's a bipoly number that's projective.

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:54.880
That's an expression. When you look at&nbsp;
it, you cannot see a circle immediately.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:55.760 --> 00:15:58.880
You have to interpret it in a&nbsp;
way so that you get a circle.

00:16:01.040 --> 00:16:04.480
But the expression actually has&nbsp;
a variety of interpretations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:11.920
and this is where things get interesting. The&nbsp;
expression is this, but the interpretations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:19.040
can be many. Let's have a look at a couple of&nbsp;
different interpretations of this expression.

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:26.000
So, our first interpretation, which we'll call&nbsp;
interpretation A, is the standard one—the one that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:35.360
we really started with. So, here is our projective&nbsp;
bipoly number C, and here it is written out as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:43.520
bipoly number in sort of alpha-beta form: -1 +&nbsp;
α² + β². And I put a little bracket around here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:49.760
sort of telling us that this is a projective&nbsp;
quantity. It's not exactly a bipoly number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:56.800
because if we multiply it by 5, it's unchanged.&nbsp;
That's what the meaning of those brackets is.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:58.640 --> 00:17:05.840
Okay, so how do we interpret this object?&nbsp;
Well, we associate it with this equation—the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:13.920
equation obtained by replacing alpha with x, beta&nbsp;
with y, and setting the poly number equal to zero.

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:21.040
So, I've set it equal to zero, and then I happen&nbsp;
to have brought the 1 on the other side to make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:25.600
it more familiar, but it's really the setting&nbsp;
this equal to zero that's the crucial thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:30.800
And note that if we multiply this&nbsp;
by 5 and set it equal to zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:36.000
it's the same as if we just set this thing equal&nbsp;
to zero. That extra factor or scaling factor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:41.840
that's in there doesn't have any effect when&nbsp;
we set it equal to zero, so it's a well-defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:41.840 --> 00:17:49.520
thing to do. So, we start from the projective&nbsp;
bipoly number, we get an equation: x² + y² = 1.

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:55.840
And then we can visualize that—well,&nbsp;
actually in a number of different ways.

00:17:57.920 --> 00:18:02.400
We can look for those points x&nbsp;
and y that satisfy this equation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:09.040
and plot those points in the standard Cartesian&nbsp;
form, and we get the circle that's familiar to us.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:16.560
But somebody else can come along and say, well,&nbsp;
actually I prefer a projective point of view. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:21.840
prefer to imagine the Cartesian plane as&nbsp;
a horizontal plane, and I'm looking at it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:21.840 --> 00:18:24.400
from some vantage point with the horizon here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:31.200
So, there's the y-axis, there's the origin,&nbsp;
there's the x-axis, and then the various lines&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:31.200 --> 00:18:38.400
y = 1, y = 2, y = 3 will be spread out ahead of&nbsp;
me, increasingly closer and closer together as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:38.400 --> 00:18:46.240
they march towards the horizon, and the various&nbsp;
lines x = 1, x = 2, x = 3, they will be like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:46.240 --> 00:18:51.040
railroad tracks all meeting at this point at&nbsp;
infinity because they're parallel over here.

00:18:53.360 --> 00:18:59.840
Now, if I draw the unit circle in the same sense,&nbsp;
I look at all the points here that I can, that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:07.440
satisfy the equation, plot a lot of them, and join&nbsp;
some up with some lines, then what will appear is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:13.040
something that's not quite a circle—it'll be more&nbsp;
elliptic. In fact, it'll be exactly an ellipse,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:20.880
but nevertheless, that's a picture, almost like&nbsp;
a photograph of this thing if it were lying in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:24.960
a plane and you actually took a picture&nbsp;
of it with the horizon there as well.

00:19:27.360 --> 00:19:35.680
Here's another variant where we still have&nbsp;
Cartesian axes, but the spacing in the x&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:42.720
and the y directions is different. Why not?&nbsp;
That's sometimes useful, and then when we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:49.520
plot the points that satisfy this, we get a shape&nbsp;
which is again an ellipse—it's a stretched circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:56.720
which is an ellipse. Another variant on that is&nbsp;
this one over here, where we've taken our axes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:56.720 --> 00:20:02.400
to be not rectangular—x-axis in&nbsp;
this direction, y-axis up there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:10.000
perhaps not equal scaling. We can still plot the&nbsp;
points x and y that satisfy the equation. When&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:19.840
we do so, we'll get another ellipse—this&nbsp;
is an affine transformation of this one.

00:20:21.200 --> 00:20:27.120
And now let's enlarge our thinking even more.&nbsp;
Let's suppose that we're visited by a creature&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:35.280
from outer space which is blind. It doesn't have&nbsp;
nice hands like we do; it has some very broad&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:36.240 --> 00:20:42.480
sort of planks that it uses for hands, so&nbsp;
anything that's two-dimensional is pretty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:42.480 --> 00:20:48.320
well invisible to it. It needs to feel something&nbsp;
three-dimensional in order to get a sense of what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:48.320 --> 00:20:53.920
we're talking about. So, to such a creature,&nbsp;
if we wanted to represent our unit circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:55.040 --> 00:21:00.720
drawing it on a piece of paper or even braising&nbsp;
it a little bit like in a braille would not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:06.480
be good enough. But what we could do is we&nbsp;
could build a cylinder on top of this thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:07.360 --> 00:21:11.840
So, here's a picture of the xy plane&nbsp;
now, sort of horizontally laid out.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:12.880 --> 00:21:18.560
This unit circle here is now along here,&nbsp;
and I've built a cylinder on top of it.

00:21:21.280 --> 00:21:25.920
So, our friend from this other planet could&nbsp;
come along and could feel the cylinder&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:30.720
and say, ah, that looks like the unit circle—now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:31.680 --> 00:21:34.080
I know what you're talking about. You're&nbsp;
talking about the unit circle—he can feel that.

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:41.920
In fact, anything that you can represent&nbsp;
two-dimensionally in terms of some kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:48.560
of curve or conic or whatever you have, you&nbsp;
can always sort of extend it up—directly up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:52.480
making a three-dimensional&nbsp;
model, essentially, that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:52.480 --> 00:21:59.120
entity could get a grasp of by grasping this.&nbsp;
So, the sides of it, rather than just the base.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:04.240
So maybe, from that person's point of&nbsp;
view or that creature's point of view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:09.440
this thing really ought to be interpreted&nbsp;
as this cylinder-type of object—really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:10.320 --> 00:22:14.320
contains the same amount of information.&nbsp;
If we agree to always go vertically up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:15.840 --> 00:22:20.480
the unit circle, the cylinder built on&nbsp;
top of it is pretty well equivalent.

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:27.360
Here's a variant on that&nbsp;
where we, for some reason,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:34.880
agree to take our unit circle in the base plane&nbsp;
xy and to build a three-dimensional object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:40.560
which is obtained by drawing all kinds of lines&nbsp;
from the circle up to a particular point above&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:40.560 --> 00:22:45.920
it—so kind of some kind of cone. So, we can&nbsp;
imagine some other kind of creature which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:51.440
physically oriented so that it can feel that&nbsp;
kind of object—maybe, maybe not this kind.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:56.560
To such a creature, they could feel this&nbsp;
and say, ah, that looks like a unit circle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:01.760
So again, there's something equivalent about&nbsp;
whether we're talking about the circle or whether&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:08.240
we're talking about this cone built on top of&nbsp;
it. They're all possible visualizations of this.

00:23:10.720 --> 00:23:17.440
So, this is the idea that to say that a circle&nbsp;
is exactly this is a little bit too limiting—it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:23.760
too narrow-minded. There are different&nbsp;
ways of thinking about a circle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:25.040 --> 00:23:29.120
That equation is actually more&nbsp;
fundamental than any of these pictures.

00:23:31.200 --> 00:23:36.080
And more fundamental than that equation&nbsp;
is this projective bipoly number from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:36.080 --> 00:23:41.280
which the equation comes. That's&nbsp;
the expression; these are various&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:42.480 --> 00:23:50.720
pictures, visualizations, interpretations of&nbsp;
the object. So, that was interpretation A.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:51.440 --> 00:23:54.160
Now I'm going to give you a&nbsp;
quite different interpretation.

00:23:56.320 --> 00:24:03.200
Same unit circle represented as a projective&nbsp;
bipoly number—there it is again—but now we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:08.720
going to look at that and associate with&nbsp;
it something rather different. We're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:17.440
to associate it with the graph z = -1 + x² + y².&nbsp;
So, we replace the alpha with the x and the beta&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:17.440 --> 00:24:26.000
with the y as before, and now we have a third&nbsp;
variable or a third poly number, if you like,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:30.560
and we're going to plot points&nbsp;
with three coordinates—coordinate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:32.080 --> 00:24:39.200
x, coordinate y, and the z or the third&nbsp;
coordinate—this value here, -1 + x² + y².&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:45.920
We're going to plot that for various&nbsp;
points x and y in the base plane,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:50.240
and then somehow or another, we're going to&nbsp;
join the dots to get some kind of surface.

00:24:55.760 --> 00:25:03.040
Okay, so what does it look like? Well, here is&nbsp;
a representation of three-dimensional space—it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:04.240 --> 00:25:08.560
a pretty well standard representation. I don't&nbsp;
think I've talked very much about this—there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:17.600
an x-axis here, a y-axis here, and a z-axis going&nbsp;
up. When looking at it, you should think of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:17.600 --> 00:25:23.920
x-axis as coming out at you, and the x and&nbsp;
y-axes are sort of being on a horizontal plane&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:31.280
with the z-axis being vertical. Now, for a little&nbsp;
bit more information about this three-dimensional&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:37.520
setup, I recommend my WildLinAlg number 9 lecture,&nbsp;
which is three-dimensional affine geometry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:37.520 --> 00:25:43.360
which gives us more detail about what&nbsp;
this coordinate system looks like.

00:25:47.440 --> 00:25:52.640
So, what we're planning to do here is we're&nbsp;
going to take various points in the xy plane,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:52.640 --> 00:25:58.320
for example, say the point (2, 1). So, the&nbsp;
point (2, 1) is there, and in the plane,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.320 --> 00:26:04.080
it would be the point roughly like there, and&nbsp;
then we evaluate this thing here at the point (2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:04.080 --> 00:26:08.240
1). So, let x be 2 and y be 1, we get altogether&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:09.840 --> 00:26:16.160
telling us that the z coordinate associated with&nbsp;
this point would be 4. So, we're going to plot (2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:20.960
1, 4), which is some point which is on&nbsp;
this surface—the surface is in green.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:28.000
It's an elliptic paraboloid—it's actually a&nbsp;
circular paraboloid, which means it's like a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:34.720
parabola except that it's been rotated, and a&nbsp;
cross-section is, in general, an ellipse—this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:35.680 --> 00:26:39.120
is a very circular one. So, if you take&nbsp;
the cross section, you actually get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.120 --> 00:26:45.120
the unit circle. So, in other words, if z =&nbsp;
0 and we're just looking at the cross section&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:50.400
of this thing—so we're slicing it where&nbsp;
it meets the plane z = 0, in other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:56.320
the xy plane—then we're getting the unit&nbsp;
circle that we were talking about before.

00:27:00.320 --> 00:27:06.240
Now, you may notice that in my&nbsp;
scaling of this three-dimensional&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:07.040 --> 00:27:11.973
reference frame, I have the x coordinate scaled,&nbsp;
and the y coordinate scaled, and along the z&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:11.973 --> 00:27:17.360
coordinates, I have some markings, but I don't&nbsp;
have any numbers. Why didn't I have any numbers?

00:27:19.520 --> 00:27:20.960
Well, because

00:27:23.520 --> 00:27:30.960
we're actually thinking of this bipoly number&nbsp;
only up to scaling. If we multiply it by 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:37.120
it's really the same projective object. That&nbsp;
means if we multiply this by 5 and replace&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:37.120 --> 00:27:40.400
this with 5 times itself, we should&nbsp;
really end up having the same object.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:47.840
That will not happen if I actually introduce&nbsp;
scaling like 1, 2, -1. Then I will have a specific&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:48.640 --> 00:27:55.280
elliptic paraboloid. By avoiding scaling&nbsp;
here, I'm incorporating the scaling—that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:04.560
the projective aspect of this bipoly number.&nbsp;
So, in other words, with one type of scaling,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:04.560 --> 00:28:06.720
this might be 1, and this might be 2. With another&nbsp;
scaling, this might be 2, and this would be 4.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:06.720 --> 00:28:16.000
With another scaling, this might be 100, and this&nbsp;
might be 200. So, this picture represents all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:23.440
of them somehow at once—it's a bit of a trick to&nbsp;
incorporate the projective aspect into a diagram.

00:28:29.040 --> 00:28:34.800
It's really well worth thinking about this. Okay,&nbsp;
so what we've done is, instead of thinking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:34.800 --> 00:28:44.400
the unit circle as this circle in the usual way in&nbsp;
the xy plane, we're now thinking about some larger&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:50.640
object—a surface in three-dimensional space whose&nbsp;
cross-section happens to be that original circle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:52.160 --> 00:28:55.120
Now, both of them came from this bipoly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:56.800 --> 00:29:00.240
so it's really only a point of&nbsp;
view that separates the two.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:01.600 --> 00:29:08.720
You can say, "This is the circle." Someone&nbsp;
else can say, "No, no, this is the circle."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:09.840 --> 00:29:12.720
You're both just interpreting the expression.

00:29:14.960 --> 00:29:18.320
Neither of you can claim to&nbsp;
be completely correct—both&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:25.840
of you are just expressing a point of view&nbsp;
about how to interpret the expression.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:31.840
Which is a better way might depend on the&nbsp;
application—it might depend on the richness of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:32.400 --> 00:29:38.720
results and understanding that result. We're going&nbsp;
to see that this, in fact, this interpretation B&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:38.720 --> 00:29:44.320
is a very powerful way to think about what&nbsp;
a unit circle is. It's a very powerful way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:49.920
so please give this some serious&nbsp;
thought—it might be a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:49.920 --> 00:29:56.640
novel thinking to you to think of this unit&nbsp;
circle as actually being that elliptic paraboloid.

00:29:57.840 --> 00:30:01.760
So, to better understand the distinction&nbsp;
between these two interpretations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:02.400 --> 00:30:07.840
let's go back to a simpler&nbsp;
one-dimensional situation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:13.120
We're going to consider the case of just&nbsp;
a poly number instead of a bipoly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:20.000
but it'll be a projective bipolar number.&nbsp;
So, suppose that we consider this projective&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:28.240
(-6, 1, 1) and it's written in kind of&nbsp;
row form, so probably we should use betas.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:29.680 --> 00:30:35.040
So, there it is, there—it's -6 + β + β²,&nbsp;
and it has little brackets in here telling&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:39.920
us that it's a projective object, meaning if&nbsp;
we multiply it by 7, it really hasn't changed.

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:51.760
Okay, so there are two possible interpretations&nbsp;
of what this thing is. One is interpretation A,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:51.760 --> 00:30:56.640
which, analogous to the previous discussion,&nbsp;
would say the following: What we need to do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:56.640 --> 00:31:01.440
is we need to take this thing here, replace beta,&nbsp;
say, with x's to make it a little more familiar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:06.080
so now we have -6 + x + x²,&nbsp;
and we set it equal to zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:07.040 --> 00:31:12.800
and we look for solutions. So, we're setting the&nbsp;
thing equal to zero and looking for solutions.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:14.080 --> 00:31:19.120
There's only one variable, so there's only&nbsp;
one line on which the solutions can live—we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:23.360
talking about x values that&nbsp;
satisfy this quadratic equation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:24.960 --> 00:31:31.840
and I hope you can all solve that quadratic&nbsp;
for us. So, x = 2 is one solution, and we get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:31.840 --> 00:31:39.280
4 + 2 - 6, that's zero, and another one is&nbsp;
-3, that would be 9 - 3 - 6, it's also zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:39.280 --> 00:31:47.760
So, that's a picture of the solutions to this&nbsp;
equation—this is sort of a one-dimensional analog&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:56.560
of the picture of the unit circle, which was x²&nbsp;
+ y² = 1, solutions to that, solutions to this.

00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:05.280
Now, the second interpretation, interpretation&nbsp;
B—what is it going to do? It's going to associate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:05.280 --> 00:32:11.040
with the same polynomial a graph. We're&nbsp;
going to introduce another variable, say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:11.040 --> 00:32:21.360
y, and we're going to graph y = -6 + x + x²,&nbsp;
going from one dimension to two dimensions. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:21.360 --> 00:32:28.560
that's the kind of thing that we've been talking&nbsp;
about, about graphing poly numbers, and okay, it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:28.560 --> 00:32:38.320
a parabola—it looks like this. I've deliberately&nbsp;
left the scaling on the y-axis out so that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:40.240 --> 00:32:46.240
well, so that the scaling, which is&nbsp;
inherent here, is reflected in this picture,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:51.920
and notice that the parabola that we get&nbsp;
has to go through the points 2 and -3.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:53.600 --> 00:32:59.120
So, the cross-section of the parabola by this&nbsp;
line gives us the one-dimensional picture of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:59.120 --> 00:33:05.680
interpretation A. This interpretation B is a&nbsp;
bigger picture that somehow is telling us more,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:11.200
but it maybe is more work to get&nbsp;
it, but maybe not because, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:17.680
we don't have to solve any quadratic equations&nbsp;
to graph it—we just have to plot a lot of points,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:18.240 --> 00:33:23.840
which is straightforward but laborious,&nbsp;
perhaps, if we want a good picture.

00:33:24.960 --> 00:33:28.640
So, please make sure you understand&nbsp;
how this distinction in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:29.360 --> 00:33:33.280
smaller case is an exact reflection&nbsp;
of the distinction between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.840
interpretation A and interpretation B&nbsp;
of the unit circle that we talked about.

00:33:39.920 --> 00:33:44.160
Okay, well worth really giving&nbsp;
these things some careful thought.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:45.600 --> 00:33:49.120
So, let's go back to our unit circle.&nbsp;
We had these two interpretations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:49.120 --> 00:33:54.080
interpretation A, interpretation B. I want&nbsp;
to now talk about another example—another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:55.280 --> 00:34:00.320
important example, in fact, I want to talk&nbsp;
about the second most important circle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:01.520 --> 00:34:06.560
The unit circle is the most important circle;&nbsp;
this one is the second most important circle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:07.920 --> 00:34:14.640
Let's have a look at it. Its name is D.&nbsp;
It's also given by a projective poly number.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:15.440 --> 00:34:20.320
It looks a lot like the unit circle one, except&nbsp;
that instead of having a -1 here, it has a +1.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:22.320 --> 00:34:27.680
As a bipoly number in alpha&nbsp;
and beta, it's 1 + α² + β².

00:34:31.680 --> 00:34:35.440
Projectively, now, let's look at this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:35.440 --> 00:34:39.680
from those two different points of&nbsp;
view—interpretation A, interpretation B.

00:34:42.240 --> 00:34:49.520
So, interpretation A—what we do is we associate&nbsp;
with this thing an equation obtained by replacing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:49.520 --> 00:34:56.720
alpha with x, beta with y, setting everything&nbsp;
equal to zero. So, if we set everything to zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:56.720 --> 00:35:01.680
and then maybe we can bring the -1 to&nbsp;
the other side, we get x² + y² = -1.

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:09.280
And now what we should do is we should graph as&nbsp;
many points that satisfy this as we can find.

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:18.080
Okay, but x² + y² = -1—that's not&nbsp;
really a circle in the standard&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:25.680
framework because there are no points x and&nbsp;
y that satisfy that equation. x² and y² are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:30.640
always positive—when you add them, you still get&nbsp;
a positive number, you're not going to get -1.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:35.760
Not until we go into the complex numbers,&nbsp;
which we have not talked about yet.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:36.800 --> 00:35:43.840
So, over the rational numbers, no&nbsp;
solutions—the picture of this thing is empty.

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:50.160
It seems like there are no solutions—this is&nbsp;
completely uninteresting. How can Wildberger&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:50.160 --> 00:35:54.480
possibly say this is the second most&nbsp;
important circle? It doesn't even exist!&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:56.320 --> 00:36:02.160
Well, it depends on how you look at it. Let's&nbsp;
look at it with the eyes of interpretation B.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:03.200 --> 00:36:10.800
What do we do there? We associate with this&nbsp;
thing a graph. We take the same expression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:10.800 --> 00:36:18.640
1 + x² + y², introduce a third variable, say z,&nbsp;
and then we're going to graph z = 1 + x² + y².

00:36:21.200 --> 00:36:29.120
Okay, there's our axis again—x, y, z. You might&nbsp;
want to play around with this if you haven't much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:33.520
experience with this kind of three-dimensional&nbsp;
plotting, trying to visualize what happens.

00:36:36.800 --> 00:36:41.200
That's made easier sometimes by setting one&nbsp;
of the variables equal to zero. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:41.200 --> 00:36:45.280
you might set y equal to zero and see what&nbsp;
happens—that's sort of this cross-section,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:50.160
that'll be a parabola—or set x equal&nbsp;
to zero, or set z equal to zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:57.440
If you set z equal to zero, well then we're back&nbsp;
to this equation here—we're asking where does this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:57.440 --> 00:37:03.120
thing intersect the xy plane? The answer is&nbsp;
nowhere. And we can see geometrically why it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:03.120 --> 00:37:07.440
doesn't have solutions, because this graph&nbsp;
is one of these elliptic paraboloids—the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:07.440 --> 00:37:16.080
same kind as we saw earlier, except that it's&nbsp;
based up here rather than below, so it's just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:16.080 --> 00:37:23.600
going up from here. There's no way it actually&nbsp;
meets the xy plane. Nevertheless, it's just as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:24.400 --> 00:37:30.400
pleasant a geometrical object as the elliptic&nbsp;
paraboloid that we got for the unit circle.

00:37:32.720 --> 00:37:36.160
So, with this interpretation B,&nbsp;
suddenly we're getting something—we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:36.160 --> 00:37:40.000
seeing something that we don't&nbsp;
see with interpretation A.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:41.840 --> 00:37:52.400
Alright, that's good, but there is more. There is&nbsp;
a third important interpretation—interpretation C.

00:37:55.520 --> 00:38:02.000
Ultimately, perhaps interpretation C will be&nbsp;
even more important than interpretations A and B.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:08.000
We're going to see later on in this series, when&nbsp;
we start talking about algebraic geometry more,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:17.120
how the idea contained in this slide ends up&nbsp;
having very big ramifications. Okay, so this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:17.120 --> 00:38:22.640
is the tip of an iceberg, and I'm just touching&nbsp;
on it now to plant some seeds in your minds.

00:38:25.040 --> 00:38:36.480
What is interpretation C? Well, here is our unit&nbsp;
circle again: -1 + α² + β². We're going to take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:36.480 --> 00:38:42.640
this thing, and we're going to associate with it&nbsp;
something slightly new—we're going to associate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:42.640 --> 00:38:51.040
with it a correspondence between two points in the&nbsp;
plane. So, instead of having just a single point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:51.040 --> 00:38:59.680
(x, y) and asking, does x² + y² = 1? We're going&nbsp;
to take two points and ask something about both&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:59.680 --> 00:39:06.640
of those points. So, the point A₁ is (x₁, y₁),&nbsp;
the point A₂ is (x₂, y₂), and we're going to ask,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:07.600 --> 00:39:17.200
is x₁x₂, which is replacing the α², plus&nbsp;
y₁y₂, which is replacing the β², equal to 1?

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:27.680
So, in interpretation A, we had x² +&nbsp;
y². Now we're breaking that x² into not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:27.680 --> 00:39:34.320
x times x, but x₁ times x₂, and we're&nbsp;
breaking the y² into y₁ times y₂.

00:39:37.920 --> 00:39:44.240
This makes things a little bit more complicated,&nbsp;
but it also makes things dramatically simpler.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:45.440 --> 00:39:49.120
How? Well, first of all, it makes things more&nbsp;
complicated because there are two points now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:49.120 --> 00:39:54.320
instead of one—we're talking about a relationship&nbsp;
between two points. So, what we're saying is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:54.880 --> 00:40:00.480
if there's a point A₁ and there's a point A₂,&nbsp;
then these two points may or may not satisfy this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:00.480 --> 00:40:06.480
correspondence. Okay, most of the time, they will&nbsp;
not satisfy this, but every so often, they will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:06.480 --> 00:40:13.920
satisfy this relation, and then those two points&nbsp;
are special. So, we want to graph both of them at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:13.920 --> 00:40:23.120
once. We want to find all pairs that satisfy&nbsp;
this relation—that sounds more complicated.

00:40:23.120 --> 00:40:26.240
But what makes it simpler is this observation:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:35.920
If you fix one of the points, you fix it, and you&nbsp;
ask the question, what are the points A₂ which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:35.920 --> 00:40:43.760
are in correspondence with that fixed A₁? Then&nbsp;
it's a linear equation in the coordinates of x₂.

00:40:45.920 --> 00:40:53.520
You're getting a line—so the points A₂ which are&nbsp;
in correspondence with a fixed A₁ lie on a line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:55.280 --> 00:40:56.160
and conversely.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:05.440
So, I'm going to leave it to you as an exercise to&nbsp;
sketch a number of these lines. So, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:13.920
if we're talking about the point (2, 0), if A₁ was&nbsp;
(2, 0), then this equation would read, that's x₂&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:14.640 --> 00:41:19.760
and that's zero. So that term would&nbsp;
die—it would be 2x₂ = 1, or x₂ = ½.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:25.600
That's an equation—x₂ = ½&nbsp;
represents this line right here.

00:41:28.400 --> 00:41:33.840
So, all the points which are in correspondence&nbsp;
with (2, 0) are the points lying on this line.

00:41:37.840 --> 00:41:41.280
This is called the polar-pole&nbsp;
correspondence, and it plays&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:48.320
a very big role in projective geometry—it's a very&nbsp;
important way of thinking about the unit circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:50.160 --> 00:41:55.200
and in some sense, it's the most&nbsp;
important aspect of a unit circle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:56.880 --> 00:42:05.520
And just to give you a little bit more examples,&nbsp;
the polar of this point here is this green line&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:05.520 --> 00:42:11.280
here, the polar of this point here is this&nbsp;
blue line here, the polar of this black point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:11.280 --> 00:42:19.280
is this black one here, and you can see,&nbsp;
perhaps, that if the blue point lies on the red&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:20.480 --> 00:42:27.440
polar, then the red point lies on the blue&nbsp;
polar. You can maybe investigate why that is.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:28.560 --> 00:42:32.640
This is just a very brief introduction to this&nbsp;
idea—we're going to talk more about this later.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:32.640 --> 00:42:37.200
I want to get you to think about the idea&nbsp;
that there are more than one interpretation.

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:43.440
Let's have a look at this interpretation of the&nbsp;
second most important circle—that invisible circle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:43.440 --> 00:42:52.080
that we introduced. Okay, so let's have a look&nbsp;
at this circle D: (1, 0, 1), (0, 1), 1 + α² + β².&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:58.000
So, we're going to associate with that the&nbsp;
correspondence between these two points given&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:03.200
by this equation—same as the last one, except&nbsp;
there's a -1 now on this side instead of a +1.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:05.200 --> 00:43:10.800
Okay, so here now I've explicitly shown you&nbsp;
the lines that you get that correspond to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:10.800 --> 00:43:23.120
various points A₁. If A₁ is (2, 1), then we get&nbsp;
the line 2x₂ + y₂ = -1. And if A₁ is (-1, 1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:24.080 --> 00:43:32.800
then we get the line -x₂ + y₂ = -1. And if A₁&nbsp;
is the line (0, -1), we get the line that's (0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:33.680 --> 00:43:41.920
-y₂) = -1, or y₂ = 1. So, this is the first case.&nbsp;
If A₁ is up here at the point (2, 1), then here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:52.720
its polar line. If A₁ is the point (-1, 1), which&nbsp;
happens to lie on this polar line, then its polar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:52.720 --> 00:44:00.240
line of this point is this line here. And if A₁ is&nbsp;
(0, -1), the point where they happen to meet, then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:00.240 --> 00:44:08.080
the polar line, I haven't drawn it, is the line&nbsp;
y₂ = 1—it would go through those two points there.

00:44:08.080 --> 00:44:13.680
It turns out that this polar-polar relationship&nbsp;
is very, very important. Okay, it's crucially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:13.680 --> 00:44:18.800
important for many things in geometry,&nbsp;
but—and I'll explain that at some later point.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:19.760 --> 00:44:24.400
So, the message today is I've just&nbsp;
started to introduce this idea that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:24.400 --> 00:44:32.400
expressions are more important than objects. Okay,&nbsp;
it maybe goes against our highly visual nature—we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:32.400 --> 00:44:40.480
like to see things, and that's good. Okay, but our&nbsp;
computers prefer expressions—concrete, explicit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:40.480 --> 00:44:50.080
expressions with numbers, preferably numbers&nbsp;
arranged in nice, concrete, organized fashions.

00:44:52.160 --> 00:44:58.320
So, this point of view—expressions are primary,&nbsp;
objects are something that are secondary,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:58.320 --> 00:45:04.000
that are associated with expressions, and there&nbsp;
may be various ways of associating objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:07.600
with expressions. There may&nbsp;
be different interpretations—I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:15.200
think this is a very powerful and somewhat&nbsp;
novel idea. Okay, somewhat novel idea.

00:45:16.560 --> 00:45:21.120
Next time, we're going to develop&nbsp;
the implications of having this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:27.360
interpretation A and interpretation B of something&nbsp;
like a unit circle. So, in fact, we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:27.360 --> 00:45:35.760
talk about calculus on the unit circle and on this&nbsp;
imaginary circle—the second most important circle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:36.960 --> 00:45:45.840
I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

